item.title: Palestinians in West Bank risk crossing Israel's separation barrier to flee failing economy
item.description: Unemployed Palestinian men in the West Bank face tremendous hardship due to restrictions and violence, leading many to risk crossing into Israel illegally for work. With soaring unemployment and mounting debts, desperate attempts have resulted in arrests, injuries, and even deaths, highlighting their dire economic situation.

item.title: Defector arrested in failed bid to return to North Korea on stolen bus
item.description: A North Korean defector was arrested after crashing a stolen bus near the DMZ while attempting to return to North Korea. Fleeing to the South in 2011, he now faces charges of theft and violating national security laws. Such crossings are infrequent, with most defectors moving from North to South.

item.title: Philippines' Taal volcano erupts, says seismology agency
Japan to keep nuclear, boost renewables in its energy mix, new industry minister says
item.description: Japan will continue safely restarting nuclear power plants and expand renewable energy usage under new Prime Minister Shigeru Ishiba. Despite his initial opposition to nuclear power, Ishiba now supports increased use of renewables and nuclear energy to meet growing electricity demand and manage living costs.

item.title: Former British PM claims Queen Elizabeth II was battling with bone cancer before death
item.description: Former British PM Boris Johnson may have breached royal protocol by revealing in his memoir that Queen Elizabeth II had bone cancer before her death. Johnson recalls her mental sharpness but physical frailty during their final meeting two days before she passed away.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Olivia Nuzzi accuses ex-fiancé of blackmail over 'affair with RFK Jr'
item.description: After accusing former fiancé Ryan Lizza of harassment and blackmail, Olivia Nuzzi obtained a no-contact order against him. Amid the legal battle, Nuzzi revealed an undisclosed relationship with a subject matter, prompting New York magazine to place her on leave pending a review of her actions while reporting on Kennedy's campaign.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: 'Make no mistake, US is fully, fully supportive of Israel': Biden after Iran's missile attack
item.description: The Biden administration differentiates between Israel's military actions and Iran's missile attack, condemning Iran’s escalation. He also made the administration's stance clear, and warned, "Make no mistake, the United States is fully, fully supportive of Israel." US pledges full support for Israel, lauds the defensive success against the missiles, and monitors the significant escalation while expressing condolences for a related terrorist incident.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Two blasts near Israel embassy in Denmark; probe initiated
item.description: Police investigated two explosions near the Israeli embassy in Copenhagen, occurring amidst heightened Middle East tensions. No injuries were reported, and a potential link to the embassy is being probed. The area also houses other foreign missions, including those of Iran and Turkey.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: ‘Border Czar’: JD Vance’s label for Kamala Harris at vice presidential debate explained
item.description: JD Vance criticised US vice president Kamala Harris as the "border czar" during the vice presidential debate, blaming her for the dismantling of Trump's immigration policies. He claimed this led to increased fentanyl influx, strained resources, and rising housing costs. Harris was tasked with addressing migration root causes but lacked authority to set immigration policy.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: 'Trump absolutely thrilled with JD Vance's performance'
item.description: Donald Trump's senior adviser praised JD Vance's debate performance, reflecting Trump's approval. Trump compared Governor Tim Walz to Kamala Harris, calling both incompetent. Trump used social media to highlight Vance's strength and undermine Walz's credibility through personal attacks and sharp commentary.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: 'How many people ...': Elon Musk takes aim at Hollywood amid explosive allegations against Diddy
item.description: Elon Musk questioned the knowledge of the music industry regarding the growing allegations against Sean 'Diddy' Combs, who faces multiple lawsuits for severe misconduct, including sexual and physical abuse. Attorney Tony Buzbee revealed 120 accusers, including minors, have come forward. Diddy's team has not yet responded to these claims.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: 'I’ve become friends with school shooters': Tim Walz makes bizarre debate gaffe; draws backlash
item.description: Minnesota governor Tim Walz misspoke during a debate on school shootings, saying he had 'become friends with school shooters,' causing social media uproar. He clarified his emotional experiences with victims' families. Tim Walz emphasised gun control, while Ohio Senator JD Vance focused on enhancing school security. Both condemned school shootings, sharing a brief moment of empathy.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: US sends warships to Middle East as tension between Israel and Iran escalates
item.description: Following increased tension in the Middle East, marked by Iran's attack on Israel, the Pentagon has directed the nuclear-powered USS Abraham Lincoln to stay in the region, with USS Harry S. Truman en route. This move ensures a significant US military presence, supporting Israel and countering regional threats. Additional forces include the Wasp Amphibious Group and guided missile destroyers.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: 'You mean because they had a headache?': Trump controversially downplays impact of Iran's attack on US troops
item.description: Former President Trump faced questions about his handling of a 2020 Iranian missile strike that caused over 100 US service members to suffer mild traumatic brain injuries. Trump downplayed the injuries, claiming no missiles hit the base, despite reports of affected personnel.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Brazil President Lula da Silva's flight faces technical error, returns to Mexico after circling four hours
item.description: A plane carrying Brazilian President Lula da Silva returned to Brasília safely after circling Mexico City due to a technical issue. Lula, who was attending Mexico's presidential inauguration, was transferred to another aircraft. The Brazilian air force confirmed that safety procedures were followed and the presidential jet consumed fuel before landing.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Immigration, climate change and Middle East: Key takeaways from Walz vs Vance vice presidential debate
item.description: US Senator JD Vance and Minnesota governor Tim Walz clashed in a high-stakes debate as vice-presidential candidates for Trump and Harris. Key issues included the Middle East, past misstatements, climate change, and immigration. Both candidates emphasized their critiques of each other's running mates, aiming to sway undecided voters ahead of the November 5 election.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: It's 'immigrants eating pets' claim once again that causes uproar, leads to muting of mics at vice presidential debate
item.description: CBS News silenced the microphones of Republicans JD Vance and Democrat Tim Walz during a heated debate about Haitian migrants in Springfield, Ohio. Vance attempted to justify his claims about migration, while Walz refuted them, leading to a fact-check by the moderator.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: 'Was wrong about Donald Trump': JD Vance on once comparing running mate to Hitler
item.description: Ohio Senator JD Vance acknowledged his past criticisms of Donald Trump, now serving as Trump's running mate. He admitted to being wrong, citing Trump's achievements during his presidency and emphasised the importance of honesty and a desire to improve governance moving forward.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: 'Knucklehead at times': Tim Walz says 'misspoke' on claim of being in Hong Kong during Tiananmen Square protests
item.description: Minnesota governor Tim Walz faced scrutiny for inaccurate claims about being in Hong Kong during the 1989 Tiananmen Square protests. Reports reveal he was in Nebraska at the time. Admitting his mistake, Walz clarified he only arrived in China that summer. He acknowledged the error, attributing it to getting caught up in rhetoric.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk

item.title: Middle East crisis: Walz blames Trump’s 'fickle leadership', Vance says he ensured 'stability' at vice presidential debate
item.description: The vice-presidential debate centered on the Middle East crisis, with Democrat Tim Walz advocating for leadership and diplomacy, while Republican JD Vance supported an aggressive deterrence strategy. Walz credited the Biden administration for steady leadership, whereas Vance criticised them for unfreezing Iranian assets. Both provided distinct visions for US foreign policy amid escalating tensions.
item.dc:creator: TOI World Desk
